   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28602_1825_05_xx_page01.jpg"/>
            <p>	- I have written to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RopeR1">Lord Rope</persName> and have desired<lb/>
               him to request <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ParsW1">Lord Oxmantown</persName> will <choice>
                  <orig>commu-<lb/>
                  nicate</orig>
                  <reg>communicate</reg>
               </choice> his answer to you - <note>May 1825</note>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>- I have also written to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FostJ1">Leslie Foster</persName> desiring<lb/>
               him to do ditto - Both gentlemen ought I<lb/>
               think and will I hope be gratified &amp; obliged<lb/>
               by your application - I told <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FxxxL1">L F</persName> that if he did<lb/>
               not chuse to give his reasons publickly for not<lb/>
               liking your company they should not go <choice>
                  <orig>far-<lb/>
                  ther</orig>
                  <reg>farther</reg>
               </choice> than to you if he trusts them to me - But<lb/>
               I think there must be some mistake about<lb/>
               his disapproval -<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">Bellamy</persName>'s <title ref="./Workography.xml#HolyB1">bible</title>
               </hi> - I enclose a draft for ten <choice>
                  <orig>gui-<lb/>
                  neas</orig>
                  <reg>guineas</reg>
               </choice> - most willingly Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> to forward<lb/>
               any wish of yours and thank you for <choice>
                  <orig>mak-<lb/>
                  -ing</orig>
                  <reg>making</reg>
               </choice> known to me your wish - But my name<lb/>
               I cannot put down to this subscription - I do<lb/>
               not approve of the thing <hi rend="underline">as far as I know</hi> - &amp; I<lb/>
               do not know enough <add>to decide</add>
               <del>to</del> I think with you that<lb/>
               the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Quart1">Quarterly <choice>
                     <orig>Rev.</orig>
                     <reg>Review</reg>
                  </choice>
               </title> has been very intemperate &amp;<lb/>
               shews a dogmatic unchristian spirit - and I<lb/>
               should be sorry that M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">Bellamy</persName> were put down<lb/>
               by such unfair means - But as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JohnS1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. J.</persName> said no<lb/>
               man can be written down in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> by any<lb/>
               one <hi rend="underline">but himself</hi> - If M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">Bellamy</persName> be right <title ref="./Workography.xml#HolyB1">his<lb/>
               book</title> will sell without a subscription - if wrong<lb/>
               it will never sell with it - As far as I have been<lb/>
               informed the first assertion in M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">B</persName>'s prospectus<lb/>
               viz "that no translation from the Original Hebrew<lb/>
               (bible) has been made since the 128<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. year of Christ is false -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The Commissioners in the reign of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#James1">K <del/> James</persName> com-<lb/>
               pared the then translation with the Hebrew rectifying<lb/>
               whatever they thought errors and retaining only the old<lb/>
               language where they thought it gave the correct sense -<lb/>
               - This is tantamount to a complete translation - &amp; you<lb/>
               cannot call this consecrating error - They might err &amp;<lb/>
               so may M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">Bellamy</persName> at this day - But they took nothing<lb/>
               for granted as far as their judgement went - As to the addi<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28602_1825_05_xx_page02.jpg"/>
               
               tional means in the present times of understanding Hebrew<lb/>
               <del>in our days</del> whence do they come? - the new means<lb/>
               of improving in Greek are from the variety of new<lb/>
               editions of classical books lexicons &amp;c -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">Bellamy</persName> touches most important points -<lb/>
               - &amp; you will say is it not right to hear compare &amp;<lb/>
               judge? - Yes if I could judge or compare after I<lb/>
               have heard - But I have no means of doing so - It<lb/>
               must be all between hebrew scholar &amp; hebrew scholar<lb/>
               as far as human judgment goes - <del>and</del> assertion<lb/>
               against assertion - all former scholars it appears<lb/>
               are against M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellJ1">Bellamy</persName> - &amp; who are to be his judges<lb/>
               now? - Not I - that is all of which I am clear -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>But setting aside all these considerations<lb/>
               even supposing that I were convinced that I had<lb/>
               a probability of <add>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DarwC1">Darwins</persName>
               </add> important advantage from the<lb/>
               book I would not publish my name as a <choice>
                  <orig>sub-<lb/>
                  scriber</orig>
                  <reg>subscriber</reg>
               </choice> - for this reason - It has been, ever since<lb/>
               we became authors, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my father</persName>'s declared <choice>
                  <orig>princi<lb/>
                  ple</orig>
                  <reg>principle</reg>
               </choice> and mine not to take any part in any<lb/>
               religious controversy - not in any way to <choice>
                  <orig>med-<lb/>
                  dle</orig>
                  <reg>meddle</reg>
               </choice> with the subject <add>of religion</add> - This was done with my<lb/>
               own will &amp; from my own belief that it was<lb/>
               right during the many years when I wrote<lb/>
               with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">my father</persName> - No change has taken place<lb/>
               in my opinions - To make a change in my<lb/>
               practice, now that he is no more would be<lb/>
               most base - It would leave the false inference<lb/>
               open that I acted under influence and that<lb/>
               now that influence <add>has</add> ceased my conduct changes<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>- Supposing that my opinions had changed<lb/>
               I would not do this - No mortal has a right to<lb/>
               ask what they are - that is an affair between me<lb/>
               &amp; my God - But no <del>worldly</del> motive could induce<lb/>
               me to bend to the side on which I <unclear>see</unclear> my <choice>
                  <orig>world-<lb/>
                  ly</orig>
                  <reg>worldly</reg>
               </choice> interest &amp; to which my conscience and<lb/>
               understanding do not justify me in bending<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I need not say my dear friend that all this<lb/>
               is for you alone - <note>Maria E May 1825</note>
               <lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
